Note: ============================================================================
Note: ELIXIR -> HIR TRANSLATOR
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Consumes the native parser output: ElixirModule / ElixirFunction /
Note: ElixirMacro / ElixirStruct / ElixirFunctionClause / ElixirAttribute /
Note: ElixirExpression. The previous version of this file targeted a separate
Note: AST_* tag model that the parser does not produce, leaving the LANG_ELIXIR
Note: arm of the translation dispatcher non-functional. This rewrite walks the
Note: parser's native struct fields directly and emits a dictionary-shaped HIR
Note: tree compatible with the dispatcher's downstream consumers (hir_to_*
Note: emitters which inspect "node_type" string tags and named child slots).
Note: ============================================================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/elixir/elixir_parser.runa" as ElixirParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/elixir/elixir_lexer.runa" as ElixirLexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/hashtable.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR STORAGE PRIMITIVES
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
HIR nodes in the dictionary-shaped translation pipeline are untyped hashtables
keyed by string field names ("node_type", "name", "body", "clauses", ...).
Wrapping hashtable_create keeps the call sites in this file consistent with
the same vocabulary used by every other dictionary-shaped frontend
(bash_to_hir, haskell_to_hir, graphql_to_hir, etc.).
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_dict" returns Integer:
    Return proc hashtable_create from Dict
End Process

@Reasoning:
HIR list storage uses the production dynamic list primitive. Children,
clauses, generators, pairs and any other ordered HIR collection allocate
through this single helper so a future storage swap stays local.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_hir_list" returns Integer:
    Return proc list_create from List
End Process

@Reasoning:
set_dict_value is a domain alias over hashtable_set. The walker code reads
naturally with set_dict_value, but the call delegates straight to the
hashtable implementation so no semantic divergence is introduced.
@End Reasoning
Process called "set_dict_value" takes dict as Integer, key as Integer, value as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc hashtable_set from Dict with dict, key, value
End Process

@Reasoning:
list_append is the corresponding alias for list_push. Walker code reading
"append child to body" is clearer than "push" semantics inherited from the
collection module.
@End Reasoning
Process called "list_append" takes lst as Integer, item as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc list_push from List with lst, item
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: TRANSLATOR STATE
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The translator carries state for OTP-aware translation: a pattern-variable
binding set, a process-context dictionary keyed by spawn id, an actor-model
dictionary, a supervision-tree dictionary, and an otp_behaviors dictionary.
The fan-out matches the previous implementation's intent: Elixir's actor
model and OTP behaviours cannot be analysed locally and need translator-
level bookkeeping that survives across nested defmodule/def walks.
@End Reasoning
Type called "ElixirToHIRTranslator":
    pattern_variables as Integer
    process_context as Integer
    actor_model_info as Integer
    supervision_tree as Integer
    otp_behaviors as Integer
    current_module as Integer
    current_function as Integer
    spawn_id_counter as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
The constructor pre-builds every tracking dictionary so the walkers never
test for null subsystem handles. current_module / current_function start
as 0 because translation begins outside any scope; translate_module and
translate_function push and restore these pointers across nested walks.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_elixir_to_hir_translator" returns Integer:
    Let translator be a value of type ElixirToHIRTranslator
    Set translator.pattern_variables to proc hashtable_create from Dict
    Set translator.process_context to proc hashtable_create from Dict
    Set translator.actor_model_info to proc hashtable_create from Dict
    Set translator.supervision_tree to proc hashtable_create from Dict
    Set translator.otp_behaviors to proc hashtable_create from Dict
    Set translator.current_module to 0
    Set translator.current_function to 0
    Set translator.spawn_id_counter to 0
    Return translator
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MODULE TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The Elixir parser produces a single ElixirModule per source file as its
top-level AST. This translator's entry walks that module's attributes,
structs, macros, and functions in declaration order, lowering each to a
HIR dict and appending to the module's "body" list. The module HIR node
carries node_type="module" plus a "name" field; the body list is the
concatenated ordered statement stream the destination emitter consumes.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_module" takes translator as Integer, module as ElixirModule returns Integer:
    Let hir_module be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "node_type", "module"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "name", module.name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "line", module.line

    Let previous_module be translator.current_module
    Set translator.current_module to hir_module

    Let body be proc create_hir_list

    Note: Lower attributes first; they often carry @moduledoc / @spec the
    Note: destination emitter wants to render before any defs.
    For Each attr as ElixirAttribute in module.attributes:
        Let hir_attr be proc translate_attribute with translator, attr
        proc list_append with body, hir_attr
    End For

    Note: Lower struct definitions.
    For Each s as ElixirStruct in module.structs:
        Let hir_struct be proc translate_struct with translator, s, module.name
        proc list_append with body, hir_struct
    End For

    Note: Lower macros (defmacro / defmacrop). Tagged is_macro=true so the
    Note: emitter can distinguish them from runtime functions.
    For Each m as ElixirMacro in module.macros:
        Let hir_macro be proc translate_macro with translator, m
        proc list_append with body, hir_macro
    End For

    Note: Lower function definitions (def / defp).
    For Each f as ElixirFunction in module.functions:
        Let hir_func be proc translate_function with translator, f
        proc list_append with body, hir_func
    End For

    proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "body", body

    Note: Scan body for "use Behaviour" attributes to tag OTP behaviours.
    proc extract_otp_behavior_info with translator, hir_module, module

    Set translator.current_module to previous_module
    Return hir_module
End Process

@Reasoning:
The dispatcher's translate_elixir_to_hir entrypoint accepts a Module pointer
directly; this is the bridge from the wrapper's parse result into the
walker chain. translate_elixir_to_hir is invoked from the public
elixir_to_hir_from_source helper after lex+parse.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_elixir_to_hir" takes translator as Integer, module as ElixirModule returns Integer:
    Return proc translate_module with translator, module
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ATTRIBUTE TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
@-prefixed module-scope attributes lower to HIR "module_attribute" dicts
carrying the attribute name (without the @ sigil) and the lowered value
expression. The destination emitter decides whether to render as a docstring
(@moduledoc, @doc), a type spec (@spec), or a custom binding.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_attribute" takes translator as Integer, attr as ElixirAttribute returns Integer:
    Let hir_attr be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_attr, "node_type", "module_attribute"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_attr, "name", attr.name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_attr, "line", attr.line
    Let hir_value be proc translate_expression with translator, attr.value
    proc set_dict_value with hir_attr, "value", hir_value
    Return hir_attr
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
defstruct lowers to a HIR "struct" dict whose name is the enclosing module's
name (Elixir tightly couples one defstruct per module). Each field is a
dictionary with "name" and "default" keys; we emit them as HIR field dicts
into a "fields" list so destination emitters can reproduce both the field
order and the per-field defaults.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_struct" takes translator as Integer, s as ElixirStruct, module_name as String returns Integer:
    Let hir_struct be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_struct, "node_type", "struct_definition"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_struct, "name", module_name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_struct, "line", s.line

    Let fields_hir be proc create_hir_list
    For Each field in s.fields:
        Let hir_field be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir_field, "node_type", "struct_field"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_field, "name", field at key "name"
        Let default_val be field at key "default"
        If default_val is not equal to 0:
            Let hir_default be proc translate_expression with translator, default_val
            proc set_dict_value with hir_field, "default", hir_default
        End If
        proc list_append with fields_hir, hir_field
    End For

    proc set_dict_value with hir_struct, "fields", fields_hir
    Return hir_struct
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FUNCTION / MACRO TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
def / defp lower to a HIR "function" dict carrying name, arity, visibility
(is_private), and a "clauses" list. Each clause is its own HIR dict with
patterns, optional guards, and a body statement list. OTP callback
detection runs after the clauses are translated: standard GenServer /
Supervisor callbacks tag the HIR function with "otp_callback" so the
target emitter can synthesise the matching trait/interface implementation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function" takes translator as Integer, func as ElixirFunction returns Integer:
    Let hir_func be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "node_type", "function"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "name", func.name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "arity", func.arity
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "line", func.line
    If func.is_private:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "is_private", "true"
    Otherwise:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "is_private", "false"
    End If

    Let previous_function be translator.current_function
    Set translator.current_function to hir_func

    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    For Each clause as ElixirFunctionClause in func.clauses:
        Let hir_clause be proc translate_function_clause with translator, clause
        proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "clauses", hir_clauses

    proc check_otp_callback with translator, hir_func, func.name, func.arity

    Set translator.current_function to previous_function
    Return hir_func
End Process

@Reasoning:
defmacro / defmacrop share the structural layout of def: name, arity,
clauses, visibility. The is_macro=true tag distinguishes them from runtime
functions so the destination emitter can route them to its macro/template
expander where one exists, or fall back to function emission with a comment
warning otherwise.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_macro" takes translator as Integer, mac as ElixirMacro returns Integer:
    Let hir_macro be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "node_type", "macro"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "name", mac.name
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "arity", mac.arity
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "line", mac.line
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "is_macro", "true"
    If mac.is_private:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "is_private", "true"
    Otherwise:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "is_private", "false"
    End If

    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    For Each clause as ElixirFunctionClause in mac.clauses:
        Let hir_clause be proc translate_function_clause with translator, clause
        proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir_macro, "clauses", hir_clauses
    Return hir_macro
End Process

@Reasoning:
A function clause is parameters + optional guards + body. Patterns lower
via translate_pattern (which records bound variable names in the
translator's pattern_variables set). Guards lower as ordinary expressions
because the guard sub-grammar is a syntactic restriction, not a different
expression layer. Each body element is a statement-position expression;
the last body element's value is the clause's result.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_function_clause" takes translator as Integer, clause as ElixirFunctionClause returns Integer:
    Let hir_clause be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "node_type", "function_clause"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "line", clause.line

    Let hir_patterns be proc create_hir_list
    For Each pat as ElixirExpression in clause.patterns:
        Let hir_pat be proc translate_pattern with translator, pat
        proc list_append with hir_patterns, hir_pat
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "patterns", hir_patterns

    Let hir_guards be proc create_hir_list
    For Each g as ElixirExpression in clause.guards:
        Let hir_g be proc translate_expression with translator, g
        proc list_append with hir_guards, hir_g
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "guards", hir_guards

    Let hir_body be proc create_hir_list
    For Each expr as ElixirExpression in clause.body:
        Let hir_expr be proc translate_expression with translator, expr
        proc list_append with hir_body, hir_expr
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "body", hir_body

    Return hir_clause
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: EXPRESSION TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The parser produces a unified ElixirExpression carrying an expr_type
string and a per-form expr_data dictionary. This dispatcher routes each
expr_type to a specialised lowering helper; unknown types fall back to a
sentinel "unknown_expression" HIR node tagged with the source expr_type so
downstream tooling can report which form was unrecognised rather than
silently dropping a subtree.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_expression" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    If expr is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let kind be expr.expr_type

    If kind is equal to "integer":
        Return proc translate_integer_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "float":
        Return proc translate_float_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "string":
        Return proc translate_string_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "charlist":
        Return proc translate_charlist_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "atom":
        Return proc translate_atom_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "boolean":
        Return proc translate_boolean_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "nil":
        Return proc translate_nil_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "sigil":
        Return proc translate_sigil_literal with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "identifier":
        Return proc translate_identifier with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "module":
        Return proc translate_module_reference with expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "binary_op":
        Return proc translate_binary_op with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "unary_op":
        Return proc translate_unary_op with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "call":
        Return proc translate_call with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "field_access":
        Return proc translate_field_access with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "list":
        Return proc translate_list_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "tuple":
        Return proc translate_tuple_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "map":
        Return proc translate_map_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "struct":
        Return proc translate_struct_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "binary":
        Return proc translate_binary_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "fn":
        Return proc translate_fn_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "case":
        Return proc translate_case_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "cond":
        Return proc translate_cond_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "if":
        Return proc translate_if_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "with":
        Return proc translate_with_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "receive":
        Return proc translate_receive_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "try":
        Return proc translate_try_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "for":
        Return proc translate_for_expr with translator, expr
    End If
    If kind is equal to "error":
        Let hir_err be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir_err, "node_type", "error"
        proc set_dict_value with hir_err, "line", expr.line
        Return hir_err
    End If

    Let hir_unknown be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir_unknown, "node_type", "unknown_expression"
    proc set_dict_value with hir_unknown, "kind", kind
    proc set_dict_value with hir_unknown, "line", expr.line
    Return hir_unknown
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LITERAL TRANSLATORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Each Elixir literal lowers to a HIR "literal" dict carrying the source
literal_kind tag and the raw value. Distinct kinds (integer / float /
string / charlist / atom / boolean / nil / sigil) let downstream backends
re-emit the literal in the destination language's syntax without needing
to re-parse the value string.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_integer_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "integer"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_float_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "float"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_string_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "string"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_charlist_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "charlist"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_atom_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "atom"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_boolean_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "boolean"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_nil_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "nil"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_sigil_literal" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "literal_kind", "sigil"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "value", expr.expr_data at key "value"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_identifier" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "identifier"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "name", expr.expr_data at key "name"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Process called "translate_module_reference" takes expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "module_reference"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "name", expr.expr_data at key "name"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: BINARY / UNARY OPERATORS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Elixir's binary-op parser stores the operator string (e.g., "+", "|>",
"==", "++"), the left expression, and the right expression. The pipe
operator "|>" passes its left value as the first argument to the right
call, which is a distinct semantic from a generic binary op; we tag those
with node_type="pipe" so the destination emitter can route pipes into
its native pipeline construct (Elm pipe, F# pipe, Java streams) or rewrite
them as nested calls. All other binary ops produce node_type="binary_op".
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_op" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let op be expr.expr_data at key "operator"
    Let left be expr.expr_data at key "left"
    Let right be expr.expr_data at key "right"

    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    If op is equal to "|>":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "pipe"
    Otherwise:
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "binary_op"
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "operator", op
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let hir_left be proc translate_expression with translator, left
    Let hir_right be proc translate_expression with translator, right
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "left", hir_left
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "right", hir_right
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Unary operators (-, !, not, ^, &) lower to a HIR "unary_op" dict with the
operator string preserved verbatim so the emitter can re-render in the
destination language's syntax. The pin operator "^" carries pattern-match
semantics in Elixir but at the expression layer it is shaped identically
to other unary ops; the pattern-matching translator handles its semantic
meaning when ^x appears in pattern position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_unary_op" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "unary_op"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "operator", expr.expr_data at key "operator"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Let operand be expr.expr_data at key "operand"
    Let hir_operand be proc translate_expression with translator, operand
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "operand", hir_operand
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CALL / FIELD ACCESS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
A "call" expression has a callee expression (which may itself be a field
access for Module.function calls) and a list of argument expressions. We
emit a HIR "call" dict and additionally recognise three Elixir-specific
call patterns that need OTP-aware tagging:
  - spawn / spawn_link / spawn_monitor / Task.start -> "actor_spawn"
  - send -> "actor_send"
  - GenServer.call / GenServer.cast / Supervisor.start_link -> tagged
    "otp_genserver_call" / "otp_genserver_cast" / "otp_supervisor_start".
The detection happens after the generic translation so the emitted call
dict always has a complete "callee" + "arguments" payload; the OTP-flavour
tags simply re-classify the node_type and add extra fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_call" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let callee_expr be expr.expr_data at key "function"
    Let arg_list be expr.expr_data at key "arguments"

    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "call"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let hir_callee be proc translate_expression with translator, callee_expr
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "callee", hir_callee

    Let hir_args be proc create_hir_list
    Let count be length of arg_list
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let arg be arg_list at index i
        Let hir_arg be proc translate_expression with translator, arg
        proc list_append with hir_args, hir_arg
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "arguments", hir_args

    Note: Detect OTP / actor model call patterns and re-classify.
    Let callee_name be proc resolve_callee_name with callee_expr
    If callee_name is equal to "spawn":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_spawn"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "spawn_type", "spawn"
        proc track_process_spawn with translator, hir
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "spawn_link":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_spawn"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "spawn_type", "spawn_link"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "linked", "true"
        proc track_process_spawn with translator, hir
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "spawn_monitor":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_spawn"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "spawn_type", "spawn_monitor"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "monitored", "true"
        proc track_process_spawn with translator, hir
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "send":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_send"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "actor_model", "true"
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "GenServer.call":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "otp_genserver_call"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "otp_behavior", "genserver"
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "GenServer.cast":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "otp_genserver_cast"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "otp_behavior", "genserver"
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "Supervisor.start_link":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "otp_supervisor_start"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "otp_behavior", "supervisor"
    End If
    If callee_name is equal to "Task.start":
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_spawn"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "spawn_type", "task_start"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "otp_task", "true"
        proc track_process_spawn with translator, hir
    End If

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Resolves a callee expression to a flat dotted-name string. Pure identifier
callees yield their name; "Module.function" field accesses yield the
dotted form. Anything more complex (computed callee, anonymous lambda
invocation, etc.) yields "" so the OTP-pattern detector simply skips
re-classification.
@End Reasoning
Process called "resolve_callee_name" takes callee_expr as ElixirExpression returns String:
    If callee_expr is equal to 0:
        Return ""
    End If
    If callee_expr.expr_type is equal to "identifier":
        Return callee_expr.expr_data at key "name"
    End If
    If callee_expr.expr_type is equal to "module":
        Return callee_expr.expr_data at key "name"
    End If
    If callee_expr.expr_type is equal to "field_access":
        Let obj be callee_expr.expr_data at key "object"
        Let field be callee_expr.expr_data at key "field"
        Let obj_name be proc resolve_callee_name with obj
        If obj_name is equal to "":
            Return field
        End If
        Return obj_name joined with "." joined with field
    End If
    Return ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
"object.field" lowers to HIR "field_access" with translated object and
literal field name. This carries the same node shape that hir_to_*
emitters expect for record/struct field reads in their destination
languages.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_field_access" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "field_access"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    Let obj be expr.expr_data at key "object"
    Let hir_obj be proc translate_expression with translator, obj
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "object", hir_obj
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "field", expr.expr_data at key "field"
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: COMPOUND LITERALS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
List literals carry an "elements" list plus an optional "tail" (for head|
tail destructuring [h | t]). We lower elements one by one; the tail, if
present, becomes a sibling HIR node under "tail". When tail is nil the
list HIR omits the key so destination emitters can branch on its presence
to choose between proper-list and cons-pair forms.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_list_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "list"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let elements be expr.expr_data at key "elements"
    Let tail be expr.expr_data at key "tail"

    Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
    Let count be length of elements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let elem be elements at index i
        Let hir_elem be proc translate_expression with translator, elem
        proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_elem
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements

    If tail is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_tail be proc translate_expression with translator, tail
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "tail", hir_tail
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Tuples are heterogeneous fixed-size collections; Elixir uses them for
tagged returns ({:ok, value}) and pattern matching. We lower to HIR
"tuple" with elements in declaration order; the destination emitter
chooses between a real tuple (Rust, Python), a record (Java), or a
positional list depending on language capability.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_tuple_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "tuple"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let elements be expr.expr_data at key "elements"
    Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
    Let count be length of elements
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let elem be elements at index i
        Let hir_elem be proc translate_expression with translator, elem
        proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_elem
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Maps lower to HIR "map" with a "pairs" list where each pair carries
"key" and "value" sub-HIR. Preserving insertion order matches Elixir's
%{} literal semantics and aligns with destination emitters that target
ordered maps (JavaScript object, Java LinkedHashMap, Rust IndexMap).
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_map_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "map"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let pairs be expr.expr_data at key "pairs"
    Let hir_pairs be proc create_hir_list
    Let count be length of pairs
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let pair be pairs at index i
        Let k be pair at key "key"
        Let v be pair at key "value"
        Let hir_pair be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "node_type", "map_pair"
        Let hir_k be proc translate_expression with translator, k
        Let hir_v be proc translate_expression with translator, v
        proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "key", hir_k
        proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "value", hir_v
        proc list_append with hir_pairs, hir_pair
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "pairs", hir_pairs
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
%Mod{key: value, ...} lowers to HIR "struct_literal" with a "type"
identifier (the module name) and a "pairs" list of field bindings. The
emitter routes this to the destination language's named-struct constructor
or, if absent, to a tagged map.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_struct_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "struct_literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "type", expr.expr_data at key "name"

    Let pairs be expr.expr_data at key "pairs"
    Let hir_pairs be proc create_hir_list
    If pairs is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of pairs
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let pair be pairs at index i
            Let k be pair at key "key"
            Let v be pair at key "value"
            Let hir_pair be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "node_type", "struct_field_init"
            Let hir_k be proc translate_expression with translator, k
            Let hir_v be proc translate_expression with translator, v
            proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "key", hir_k
            proc set_dict_value with hir_pair, "value", hir_v
            proc list_append with hir_pairs, hir_pair
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "pairs", hir_pairs
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bitstring / binary literals <<...>> lower to HIR "binary_literal" with
elements list. Elixir uses bitstrings for protocol buffers, serialised
formats, and pattern-matching against wire data; preserving the segments
lets a destination emitter regenerate the bit-precise representation.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_binary_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "binary_literal"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let elements be expr.expr_data at key "elements"
    Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
    If elements is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let elem be elements at index i
            Let hir_elem be proc translate_expression with translator, elem
            proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_elem
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONTROL FLOW
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
fn -> ... end is the anonymous function form. The parser stores a list
of clauses (a multi-clause fn dispatches by pattern). We lower each
clause and emit a HIR "lambda" dict with clauses list, mirroring the
function/macro shape.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_fn_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "lambda"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"
    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let clause be clauses at index i
            Let hir_clause be proc translate_function_clause with translator, clause
            proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "clauses", hir_clauses
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
case e do pattern -> body ; ... end lowers to HIR "pattern_match" with
the scrutinee under "expression" and a "clauses" list of pattern + guard
+ body trios. The HIR node_type distinguishes Elixir-source-level case
from desugared matches so the gungnir lowering can choose its target
syntax.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_case_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "pattern_match"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let scrutinee be expr.expr_data at key "expression"
    Let hir_scrut be proc translate_expression with translator, scrutinee
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "expression", hir_scrut

    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"
    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let clause be clauses at index i
            Let hir_clause be proc translate_match_clause with translator, clause
            proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "clauses", hir_clauses
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A match clause (case arm) is a pattern + optional guard + body. We
delegate to translate_pattern (which records bound variable names in the
translator's pattern_variables) and translate_expression for the guard
and body. The HIR shape is identical to a function clause, but tagged
"match_clause" so destination emitters can decide whether to emit a
language-native match or unfold into a chained-if equivalent.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_match_clause" takes translator as Integer, clause as ElixirFunctionClause returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "match_clause"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", clause.line

    Let hir_patterns be proc create_hir_list
    For Each p as ElixirExpression in clause.patterns:
        Let hir_p be proc translate_pattern with translator, p
        proc list_append with hir_patterns, hir_p
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "patterns", hir_patterns

    Let hir_guards be proc create_hir_list
    For Each g as ElixirExpression in clause.guards:
        Let hir_g be proc translate_expression with translator, g
        proc list_append with hir_guards, hir_g
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "guards", hir_guards

    Let hir_body be proc create_hir_list
    For Each e as ElixirExpression in clause.body:
        Let hir_e be proc translate_expression with translator, e
        proc list_append with hir_body, hir_e
    End For
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "body", hir_body
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
cond do guard -> body ; ... end is multi-branch dispatch on boolean
guards. We lower to HIR "cond" with a "clauses" list where each clause
carries a single guard and a body. Destination emitters typically render
this as an else-if chain.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_cond_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "cond"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"
    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let clause be clauses at index i
            Let cond_expr be clause at key "condition"
            Let body_list be clause at key "body"
            Let hir_clause be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "node_type", "cond_clause"
            Let hir_cond be proc translate_expression with translator, cond_expr
            proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "condition", hir_cond
            Let hir_body be proc translate_body_list with translator, body_list
            proc set_dict_value with hir_clause, "body", hir_body
            proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "clauses", hir_clauses
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
if condition do A else B end lowers to HIR "if_statement" with condition,
then_block, and optional else_block. The parser stores then-body and
else-body as separate ElixirExpression lists.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_if_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "if_statement"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let cond be expr.expr_data at key "condition"
    Let hir_cond be proc translate_expression with translator, cond
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "condition", hir_cond

    Let then_body be expr.expr_data at key "then"
    Let hir_then be proc translate_body_list with translator, then_body
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "then_block", hir_then

    Let else_body be expr.expr_data at key "else"
    If else_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_else be proc translate_body_list with translator, else_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "else_block", hir_else
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
with <- chains lower to HIR "with_chain". Each step has a pattern and
an expression (pattern <- expr). On any pattern-match failure the with
falls through to the optional else clause. We preserve the step list
plus optional else; destination emitters can either render with as a
flat-map / monadic bind or as nested case statements.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_with_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "with_chain"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let steps be expr.expr_data at key "steps"
    Let hir_steps be proc create_hir_list
    If steps is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of steps
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let step be steps at index i
            Let pat be step at key "pattern"
            Let val be step at key "expression"
            Let hir_step be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with hir_step, "node_type", "with_step"
            Let hir_pat be proc translate_pattern with translator, pat
            proc set_dict_value with hir_step, "pattern", hir_pat
            Let hir_val be proc translate_expression with translator, val
            proc set_dict_value with hir_step, "value", hir_val
            proc list_append with hir_steps, hir_step
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "steps", hir_steps

    Let do_body be expr.expr_data at key "do"
    If do_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_do be proc translate_body_list with translator, do_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "body", hir_do
    End If

    Let else_clauses be expr.expr_data at key "else"
    If else_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_else be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of else_clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let clause be else_clauses at index i
            Let hir_clause be proc translate_match_clause with translator, clause
            proc list_append with hir_else, hir_clause
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "else", hir_else
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
receive selects messages from the process mailbox by pattern. We tag
node_type="actor_receive" so destination emitters can lower to their
native concurrency primitive (Go channel select, Java BlockingQueue.poll,
Erlang receive). The optional after clause for timeout is preserved as
a "timeout" sub-node.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_receive_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "actor_receive"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "actor_model", "true"

    Let clauses be expr.expr_data at key "clauses"
    Let hir_clauses be proc create_hir_list
    If clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let clause be clauses at index i
            Let hir_clause be proc translate_match_clause with translator, clause
            proc list_append with hir_clauses, hir_clause
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "clauses", hir_clauses

    Let after_clause be expr.expr_data at key "after"
    If after_clause is not equal to 0:
        Let timeout_expr be after_clause at key "timeout"
        Let timeout_body be after_clause at key "body"
        Let hir_after be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir_after, "node_type", "timeout_clause"
        Let hir_timeout be proc translate_expression with translator, timeout_expr
        proc set_dict_value with hir_after, "timeout", hir_timeout
        Let hir_tbody be proc translate_body_list with translator, timeout_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir_after, "body", hir_tbody
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "after", hir_after
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
try / rescue / catch / after lowers to HIR "try_statement". rescue
clauses match on exception structs, catch clauses match on throw values
(:throw / :exit / :error pairs), the after clause unconditionally runs.
We preserve all four sub-blocks so destination emitters can route to
language-appropriate exception handling.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_try_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "try_statement"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let do_body be expr.expr_data at key "do"
    If do_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_do be proc translate_body_list with translator, do_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "body", hir_do
    End If

    Let rescue_clauses be expr.expr_data at key "rescue"
    If rescue_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_rescue be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of rescue_clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let c be rescue_clauses at index i
            Let hir_c be proc translate_match_clause with translator, c
            proc list_append with hir_rescue, hir_c
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "rescue", hir_rescue
    End If

    Let catch_clauses be expr.expr_data at key "catch"
    If catch_clauses is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_catch be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of catch_clauses
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let c be catch_clauses at index i
            Let hir_c be proc translate_match_clause with translator, c
            proc list_append with hir_catch, hir_c
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "catch", hir_catch
    End If

    Let after_body be expr.expr_data at key "after"
    If after_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_after be proc translate_body_list with translator, after_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "after", hir_after
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
for-comprehensions fuse generators (pattern <- enumerable), filters
(boolean predicates), and a transform body into one expression. We lower
to HIR "list_comprehension" with generators / filters / transform as
named child slots. Generators carry their pattern + source-enumerable;
filters are plain expressions.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_for_expr" takes translator as Integer, expr as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "list_comprehension"
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", expr.line

    Let generators be expr.expr_data at key "generators"
    Let hir_generators be proc create_hir_list
    If generators is not equal to 0:
        Let count be length of generators
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let gen be generators at index i
            Let pat be gen at key "pattern"
            Let src be gen at key "source"
            Let hir_gen be proc create_hir_dict
            proc set_dict_value with hir_gen, "node_type", "generator"
            Let hir_pat be proc translate_pattern with translator, pat
            proc set_dict_value with hir_gen, "pattern", hir_pat
            Let hir_src be proc translate_expression with translator, src
            proc set_dict_value with hir_gen, "source", hir_src
            proc list_append with hir_generators, hir_gen
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If
    proc set_dict_value with hir, "generators", hir_generators

    Let filters be expr.expr_data at key "filters"
    If filters is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_filters be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of filters
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let f be filters at index i
            Let hir_f be proc translate_expression with translator, f
            proc list_append with hir_filters, hir_f
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "filters", hir_filters
    End If

    Let do_body be expr.expr_data at key "do"
    If do_body is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_transform be proc translate_body_list with translator, do_body
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "transform", hir_transform
    End If

    Let into_target be expr.expr_data at key "into"
    If into_target is not equal to 0:
        Let hir_into be proc translate_expression with translator, into_target
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "into", hir_into
    End If
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PATTERN TRANSLATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Patterns in Elixir reuse the ElixirExpression type; the parser stores
patterns in clause.patterns and tuple-element / list-element positions
inside other expressions. translate_pattern walks an expression in
pattern mode, binding variable names in translator.pattern_variables
on first encounter and recursing into composite patterns (tuple, list,
map, struct, binary). Literals lower identically to expressions because
matching a literal is structurally the same operation as evaluating it.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_pattern" takes translator as Integer, pat as ElixirExpression returns Integer:
    If pat is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let kind be pat.expr_type

    If kind is equal to "identifier":
        Let name be pat.expr_data at key "name"
        proc bind_pattern_variable with translator, name
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "pattern_variable"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "name", name
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        Return hir
    End If

    If kind is equal to "tuple":
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "tuple_pattern"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        Let elements be pat.expr_data at key "elements"
        Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let e be elements at index i
            Let hir_e be proc translate_pattern with translator, e
            proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_e
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements
        Return hir
    End If

    If kind is equal to "list":
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "list_pattern"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        Let elements be pat.expr_data at key "elements"
        Let tail be pat.expr_data at key "tail"
        Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
        Let count be length of elements
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than count:
            Let e be elements at index i
            Let hir_e be proc translate_pattern with translator, e
            proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_e
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements
        If tail is not equal to 0:
            Let hir_tail be proc translate_pattern with translator, tail
            proc set_dict_value with hir, "tail", hir_tail
        End If
        Return hir
    End If

    If kind is equal to "map":
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "map_pattern"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        Let pairs be pat.expr_data at key "pairs"
        Let hir_pairs be proc create_hir_list
        If pairs is not equal to 0:
            Let count be length of pairs
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let p be pairs at index i
                Let k be p at key "key"
                Let v be p at key "value"
                Let hir_p be proc create_hir_dict
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "node_type", "map_pattern_pair"
                Let hir_k be proc translate_expression with translator, k
                Let hir_v be proc translate_pattern with translator, v
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "key", hir_k
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "value", hir_v
                proc list_append with hir_pairs, hir_p
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "pairs", hir_pairs
        Return hir
    End If

    If kind is equal to "struct":
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "struct_pattern"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "type", pat.expr_data at key "name"
        Let pairs be pat.expr_data at key "pairs"
        Let hir_pairs be proc create_hir_list
        If pairs is not equal to 0:
            Let count be length of pairs
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let p be pairs at index i
                Let k be p at key "key"
                Let v be p at key "value"
                Let hir_p be proc create_hir_dict
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "node_type", "struct_pattern_field"
                Let hir_k be proc translate_expression with translator, k
                Let hir_v be proc translate_pattern with translator, v
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "key", hir_k
                proc set_dict_value with hir_p, "value", hir_v
                proc list_append with hir_pairs, hir_p
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "pairs", hir_pairs
        Return hir
    End If

    If kind is equal to "binary":
        Let hir be proc create_hir_dict
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "node_type", "binary_pattern"
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "line", pat.line
        Let elements be pat.expr_data at key "elements"
        Let hir_elements be proc create_hir_list
        If elements is not equal to 0:
            Let count be length of elements
            Let i be 0
            While i is less than count:
                Let e be elements at index i
                Let hir_e be proc translate_pattern with translator, e
                proc list_append with hir_elements, hir_e
                Set i to i plus 1
            End While
        End If
        proc set_dict_value with hir, "elements", hir_elements
        Return hir
    End If

    Note: Literals and operator patterns (pin ^x, |  cons) reuse the
    Note: expression translator since their HIR shape matches.
    Return proc translate_expression with translator, pat
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
translate_body_list lowers a List[ElixirExpression] body block into a
HIR list of translated statements. Used by case clauses, if/else blocks,
with do/else, try do/rescue/catch/after, receive after, for comprehension
transforms. Centralised so the body-list lowering remains uniform across
every consumer.
@End Reasoning
Process called "translate_body_list" takes translator as Integer, body as Integer returns Integer:
    Let hir_body be proc create_hir_list
    If body is equal to 0:
        Return hir_body
    End If
    Let count be length of body
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count:
        Let e be body at index i
        Let hir_e be proc translate_expression with translator, e
        proc list_append with hir_body, hir_e
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return hir_body
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a pattern-bound variable name in translator.pattern_variables.
Guard expression lowering can later consult this set to distinguish
bound names (legal in guards) from free identifiers (which would resolve
to module-level lookup). The value side stores the marker "bound" so the
set behaves as a presence test under hashtable semantics.
@End Reasoning
Process called "bind_pattern_variable" takes translator as Integer, var_name as String returns Integer:
    Return proc hashtable_set from Dict with translator.pattern_variables, var_name, "bound"
End Process

@Reasoning:
Records a process-spawning call site under a unique id in process_context.
The spawn_id_counter is bumped per call so each spawn has a distinct key
even for repeated identical call shapes. Downstream actor-graph analysis
walks this dictionary to build a process topology.
@End Reasoning
Process called "track_process_spawn" takes translator as Integer, spawn_hir as Integer returns Integer:
    Set translator.spawn_id_counter to translator.spawn_id_counter plus 1
    Let id_str be "spawn_" joined with string representation of translator.spawn_id_counter
    Return proc hashtable_set from Dict with translator.process_context, id_str, spawn_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
OTP behaviours (GenServer, Supervisor, Application, GenStage, Agent, etc.)
are declared inside a module body via `use Behaviour`. The parser stores
these as ordinary call expressions; here we walk the module's function
clauses looking for top-level `use ...` calls and record the behaviour
name in translator.otp_behaviors plus tag the HIR module dict with
otp_behavior=<name>. Multiple use statements yield multiple entries.
@End Reasoning
Process called "extract_otp_behavior_info" takes translator as Integer, hir_module as Integer, module as ElixirModule returns Integer:
    Note: Elixir's `use Behaviour` syntax appears as bare expressions in the
    Note: module body, but the parser routes those into the functions list
    Note: only if they look like def/defp; ordinary `use` calls go through
    Note: the bare-expression error-recovery path so we cannot recover them
    Note: from the structured module fields. We instead scan each function's
    Note: first body element for `use Behaviour` markers, which is how
    Note: behaviour declarations appear when they follow a def line.
    For Each f as ElixirFunction in module.functions:
        For Each clause as ElixirFunctionClause in f.clauses:
            For Each e as ElixirExpression in clause.body:
                If e.expr_type is equal to "call":
                    Let callee be e.expr_data at key "function"
                    Let name be proc resolve_callee_name with callee
                    If name is equal to "use":
                        Let args be e.expr_data at key "arguments"
                        If length of args is greater than 0:
                            Let first_arg be args at index 0
                            Let behaviour_name be proc resolve_callee_name with first_arg
                            If behaviour_name is not equal to "":
                                proc hashtable_set from Dict with translator.otp_behaviors, behaviour_name, hir_module
                                proc set_dict_value with hir_module, "otp_behavior", behaviour_name
                            End If
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End For
        End For
    End For
    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Standard OTP callback functions are identified by both name and arity:
GenServer: init/1, handle_call/3, handle_cast/2, handle_info/2, terminate/2,
code_change/3. Supervisor: init/1 (disambiguated by checking the module's
otp_behavior tag — if set to "Supervisor", init/1 is a supervisor init;
otherwise we tag it as genserver_init by default since GenServer is the
overwhelmingly more common case). Application: start/2, stop/1. Agent:
init/1. Tagging the HIR function with its canonical callback role lets
target emitters generate the right framework hooks in destination languages
that have explicit actor/service interfaces (Akka actor methods,
Java Spring lifecycle annotations, etc.).
@End Reasoning
Process called "check_otp_callback" takes translator as Integer, hir_func as Integer, name as String, arity as Integer returns Integer:
    If name is equal to "init" and arity is equal to 1:
        Let supervisor_tag be proc hashtable_get from Dict with translator.current_module, "otp_behavior"
        If supervisor_tag is equal to "Supervisor":
            proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "supervisor_init"
        Otherwise:
            proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_init"
        End If
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "handle_call" and arity is equal to 3:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_handle_call"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "handle_cast" and arity is equal to 2:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_handle_cast"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "handle_info" and arity is equal to 2:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_handle_info"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "terminate" and arity is equal to 2:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_terminate"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "code_change" and arity is equal to 3:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "genserver_code_change"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "start" and arity is equal to 2:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "application_start"
        Return 1
    End If
    If name is equal to "stop" and arity is equal to 1:
        proc set_dict_value with hir_func, "otp_callback", "application_stop"
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PUBLIC ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Public single-arg facade invoked by the translation dispatcher's
LANG_ELIXIR arm. Wires the full source -> HIR pipeline: create_lexer
builds the lexer state from the source string, lex tokenises into the
three parallel arrays (tokens/lexemes/lines), parse_elixir wraps those
arrays into an ElixirParser and parses out an ElixirModule, and
translate_elixir_to_hir lowers the module into HIR.
@End Reasoning
@Implementation:
lexer = create_lexer(source); lex(lexer); module = parse_elixir(lexer.tokens,
lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines); translator = create_elixir_to_hir_translator();
return translate_elixir_to_hir(translator, module). The pipeline returns 0
only if the lexer fails to allocate; the parser produces a partial module
on syntax errors but downstream translation still consumes it (matching
the error-recovery posture every other frontend uses).
@End Implementation
Process called "elixir_to_hir_from_source" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_lexer from ElixirLexer with source_code
    Call lex from ElixirLexer with lexer

    Let module be proc parse_elixir from ElixirParser with lexer.tokens, lexer.lexemes, lexer.lines
    Let translator be proc create_elixir_to_hir_translator
    Return proc translate_elixir_to_hir with translator, module
End Process

@Reasoning:
Dispatcher-facing entry used by the LANG_ELIXIR arm of translation.runa
when the dispatcher imports this module as ElixirParser/ElixirEmitter. The
single-arg form takes the source string and runs the full pipeline; the
dispatcher conventionally calls this as `elixir_to_hir(source)`.
@End Reasoning
Process called "elixir_to_hir" takes source_code as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc elixir_to_hir_from_source with source_code
End Process
